{
    "word": "Remark",
    "definitions": [
        "To mark in a notable manner; to distinquish clearly; to make noticeable or conspicuous; to piont out.",
        "To take notice of, or to observe, mentally; as, to remark the manner of a speaker.",
        "To express in words or writing, as observed or noticed; to state; to say; -- often with a substantive clause; as, he remarked that it was time to go.",
        "To make a remark or remarks; to comment.",
        "Act of remarking or attentively noticing; notice or observation.",
        "The expression, in speech or writing, of something remarked or noticed; the mention of that which is worthy of attention or notice; hence, also, a casual observation, comment, or statement; as, a pertinent remark."
    ],
    "examples": [
        "Thou art a man remarked to taste a mischief.",
        "His manacles remark him; there he sits.",
        "The cause, though worth the search, may yet elude Conjecture and remark, however shrewd."
    ],
    "etymology": "[F. remarquer; pref. re- re- + marquer to mark, marque a mark, of German origin, akin to E. mark. See Mark, v. & n.]"
}